3. In a database, what is the fundamental difference in data organization between Row-based storage and Column-based storage?-
   Row-based stores all values for a single row contiguously; Column-based stores all values for a single column contiguously.

4. Which column characteristic is the primary requirement for a Bitmap Index to be an efficient indexing strategy? - 
   Low Cardinality (few unique values)

5. What is the standard SQL operation or concept used to transform a column containing an array (repeated data) of structured 
   elements into a set of separate, normalized rows?   -
   UNNEST (or FLATTEN) : The UNNEST operation is used in SQL to expand an array or repeated field into multiple rows.

6. A financial company's database processes numerous complex analytical queries combining filters on three columns: 
   ProductSegment (10 values), Region (5 values), and IsSettled (True/False). 
   Which index type is most suitable for optimizing these specific read-heavy queries? - 
   Bitmap Index on all three columns   

7. A table has a B-Tree index on the creation_date column. Which of the following SQL WHERE clauses 
   will likely force a full table or full index scan instead of using the index efficiently?   --
   WHERE YEAR(creation_date) = 2024

8. Comparing Row-based and Column-based storage, 
    which statement accurately reflects their typical performance trade-offs for analytical workloads?   --- 
    Column-based storage requires less I/O when reading only a subset of columns for analysis.
    In column-based storage, data is stored column by column rather than row by row. This means that when a query only needs a few columns,
    the database reads only those columns from disk, reducing the amount of I/O.

9. An executive dashboard currently takes 15 seconds to load because it executes a complex query that joins five large tables 
   and calculates four different summary metrics. The underlying data only changes once every 24 hours. 
   The goal is to reduce the dashboard load time to under 1 second without modifying the application code that displays the data. 
   Which database object should be created to achieve this goal?    ---
   A Materialized View, refreshed daily 
   A materialized view stores the precomputed result of a query physically on disk instead of computing it every time it is requested.

10. A database stores information about customer orders. To avoid numerous JOIN operations, a single row in the Orders table contains a nested field called LineItems,
    which is an array of structs (containing productid, quantity, and price).
    A financial analyst needs to calculate the total quantity of a specific product sold across all orders. 
    Which approach is necessary to satisfy this query requirement?   ---
    Use the UNNEST operator on the Line_Items field, then filter and SUM the resulting rows.

11. What is the primary technical advantage of using a Materialized View over a standard View in a data analysis environment? --
    A standard View stores the query definition; a Materialized View stores the actual data results.

12. The primary purpose of database partitioning is to: -- 
     Break a large table into smaller, more manageable physical pieces based on a key.

13. A data warehouse team has a 5-year history table containing billions of log entries, all indexed by a log_timestamp column. 
    They need to frequently run queries that only hit the last 3 months of data, 
    and they also want to implement a cost-saving policy to archive or delete data older than 3 years easily. 
    Which partitioning strategy should they adopt?     ---
    Range Partitioning on the log_timestamp column, 
    creating monthly partitions for efficient query pruning and easy detachment of old data.

